S2 SCENARIO
You are processing 50,000 raw customer reviews scraped from a food delivery app. The
reviews contain mixed letter cases, special characters, emojis, numbers, and common
filler words such as 'the', 'is', and 'a'.

Question: Describe the text preprocessing pipeline you would apply to this dataset before
feeding it to any NLP model. Justify the order in which you would apply each step, and explain
specifically why skipping stopword removal could hurt downstream model performance.

(Answer)

Before training an NLP model, the customer reviews should go through the following text preprocessing pipeline:

Convert text to lowercase:
First, convert all text to lowercase so that words like "Food", "FOOD", and "food" are treated as the same word. This reduces duplicate representations and creates a consistent dataset.
Remove special characters, emojis, punctuation, and numbers:
Next, remove unnecessary symbols, emojis, punctuation marks, and numbers that usually do not contribute to understanding the meaning of the reviews. This helps reduce noise in the dataset.
Tokenization:
Split each review into individual words or tokens. Tokenization prepares the text for further preprocessing and feature extraction.
Stopword Removal:
Remove common words such as "the", "is", "a", and "an" because they occur frequently but usually carry very little meaningful information for text classification.
Stemming or Lemmatization:
Finally, reduce words to their root or base form. For example, "delivering", "delivered", and "delivery" can be reduced to a common base word, allowing the model to treat them as related terms.

Justification for the order:
Lowercasing is performed first to standardize the text. Cleaning special characters and numbers removes unwanted noise before tokenization. Tokenization must occur before stopword removal because stopwords are removed from individual tokens. Stemming or lemmatization is applied at the end so that the remaining meaningful words are converted to their root forms.

Why skipping stopword removal can hurt performance:
If stopwords are not removed, very common words such as "the", "is", and "a" will appear frequently in the dataset and may dominate the feature representation. These words provide little useful information for understanding customer reviews, increase the dimensionality of the data, and make it harder for the model to focus on important words such as "late", "cold", "refund", or "cancel". As a result, the model may achieve lower accuracy and require more processing time.

