S3 SCENARIO
You are building a food item search feature that must rank menu descriptions by
relevance to a customer's typed query, for example 'spicy chicken without onion'.

Question: Compare Bag of Words and TF-IDF as text representation methods for this ranking
task. Which would you choose and why? Identify one limitation that your chosen method still has
even after it is applied.

(Answer)

**Bag of Words (BoW)** and **TF-IDF (Term Frequency–Inverse Document Frequency)** are two common methods for representing text in NLP.

**Bag of Words (BoW):**
Bag of Words represents a document by counting how many times each word appears. Every word is treated equally, regardless of how common or rare it is across all documents. While this method is simple and easy to implement, it often gives high importance to frequently occurring words that may not be very informative.

**TF-IDF:**
TF-IDF assigns weights to words based on both their frequency in a document and their rarity across the entire dataset. Words that appear frequently in one document but rarely in others receive higher importance, making TF-IDF more effective at identifying meaningful keywords.

For the food item search feature, I would choose **TF-IDF** because it provides more accurate relevance ranking. For example, in the query **"spicy chicken without onion"**, important words such as **"spicy"**, **"chicken"**, and **"onion"** receive higher weights than common words, allowing the system to return menu items that better match the customer's search.

**Limitation of TF-IDF:**
Even after applying TF-IDF, the model does not understand the meaning or context of words. It treats words independently and cannot recognize synonyms, word order, or semantic relationships. For example, it may not understand that **"hot chicken"** and **"spicy chicken"** have similar meanings, which can reduce the quality of search results.

